@page "/java-keytool"

<PageTitle>Java Keytool</PageTitle>

<H1>Java Keytool</H1>

<BlockQuote>
    <BlockQuoteContent>
        This page provides concise commands for listing keystore contents, checking certificate details,
        and importing certificates (both public and private keys) using the Java keytool utility.
    </BlockQuoteContent>
    <BlockQuoteFooter>
        Useful for managing Java Keystores (JKS) for applications, servers, and secure communication.
    </BlockQuoteFooter>
</BlockQuote>

<H2>1. Listing Keystore Contents</H2>
<p>
    Display all entries in a keystore (aliases, certificates, etc.):
</p>

<CodeBlockSyntax Language="bash" EnableLineNumbers="false" EnableCopyButton="true"><pre>
keytool -list -v -keystore keystore.jks
</pre></CodeBlockSyntax>

<p>
    - <strong>-list</strong> shows the contents of the keystore.<br />
    - <strong>-v</strong> (verbose) displays detailed information about each entry.<br />
    - <strong>-keystore</strong> specifies the keystore file.
</p>

<H2>2. Checking Certificate Details</H2>
<p>
    View detailed information about a specific certificate in the keystore:
</p>

<CodeBlockSyntax Language="bash" EnableLineNumbers="false" EnableCopyButton="true"><pre>
keytool -list -v -keystore keystore.jks -alias mycert
</pre></CodeBlockSyntax>

<p>
    - <strong>-alias mycert</strong> identifies the specific certificate entry to inspect.
</p>

<H2>3. Importing a Public Certificate (PEM or CRT)</H2>
<p>
    Import a public certificate (.pem, .crt) into a keystore:
</p>

<CodeBlockSyntax Language="bash" EnableLineNumbers="false" EnableCopyButton="true"><pre>
keytool -import \
    -alias mycert \
    -file certificate.crt \
    -keystore keystore.jks
</pre></CodeBlockSyntax>

<p>
    - <strong>-file certificate.crt</strong> indicates the certificate file to be imported.<br />
    - If the alias already exists, keytool prompts you to overwrite it (unless you use <strong>-trustcacerts</strong> 
      to import into the trust store).
</p>

<H2>4. Importing a Certificate with Private Key (PEM or CRT)</H2>
<p>
    Java keytool cannot directly import a private key from PEM/CRT. Instead, you can convert it to a PKCS#12 file 
    (with both certificate and private key included), then import that into a JKS.
</p>

<p><strong>Step A: Convert PEM/CRT + private key to PKCS#12</strong></p>
<CodeBlockSyntax Language="bash" EnableLineNumbers="false" EnableCopyButton="true"><pre>
openssl pkcs12 -export \
    -in certificate.crt \
    -inkey private.key \
    -out mycert.p12 \
    -name myalias
</pre></CodeBlockSyntax>

<p>
    - <strong>myalias</strong> is an identifier you assign to the certificate+key pair in the PKCS#12 file.
</p>

<p><strong>Step B: Import the PKCS#12 file into a JKS keystore</strong></p>
<CodeBlockSyntax Language="bash" EnableLineNumbers="false" EnableCopyButton="true"><pre>
keytool -importkeystore \
    -destkeystore keystore.jks \
    -srckeystore mycert.p12 \
    -srcstoretype pkcs12 \
    -alias myalias
</pre></CodeBlockSyntax>

<p>
    - <strong>-destkeystore keystore.jks</strong> is the target Java Keystore (JKS).<br />
    - <strong>-srckeystore mycert.p12</strong> is the PKCS#12 file containing the private key and certificate.<br />
    - <strong>-srcstoretype pkcs12</strong> specifies the source file format.
</p>

<p>
    These commands provide a quick reference for common keytool operations: listing keystore contents, 
    checking certificate details, and importing both public certificates and private keys. 
    Adjust filenames, aliases, and keystore passwords to suit your requirements.
</p>